It looks like the ApartmentAttribute is not added to Test.Properties when it is applied to a Fixture. ApartmentAttributeTests all pass through (bad) luck, however it is possible to cause failures by running this test assembly with a timeout specified on the command line.

From my limited debugging and understanding of the code, it appears that when a fixture is marked with an ApartmentAttribute, a new thread is created at WorkItem.Execute, however when the child test comes to run, TargetApartment is Unknown and we call thread.SetApartmentState(TargetApartment). It seems what we really want to do is keep the parent apartment in the case where there is no TargetApartment and we are starting a new thread (because of the non-zero timeout).

```
@@ -240,7 +240,7 @@ namespace NUnit.Framework.Internal.Execution
            ApartmentState currentApartment = Thread.CurrentThread.GetApartmentState();

            if (Test.RequiresThread || Test is TestMethod && timeout > 0 || currentApartment != TargetApartment && TargetApartment != ApartmentState.Unknown)
-                RunTestOnOwnThread(timeout, TargetApartment);
+                RunTestOnOwnThread(timeout, TargetApartment == ApartmentState.Unknown ? currentApartment : TargetApartment);
            else
                RunTest();
#endif
```
